					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">On a given video system, scanlines will always be the same height. As for the width of pixels, it's probably easiest to express those as fractions of the NTSC color subcarrier's period. (One period is 1/3579545 second, or 3/560 of a scanline.) Square pixels in 240p are 7/12 of a period wide, and CCIR 601 pixels are 35/132 period (=39.375*11/13.5) wide. Atari 2600 pixels were a full period wide, NES/SMS/SNES pixels were 2/3, and Genesis pixels were 8/15. Apple II pixels were a full color period wide or half a color period wide, depending on whom you ask, because of its unique "direct subpixel" way of generating colors in high-resolution mode.
<br />
<br />I <em>think</em> pixels in C64 multicolor mode are a full period wide, but I have no C64 to test my conjecture on. If this is the case, then sixteen C64 multicolor pixels equal 24 NES pixels across.</div>

